# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: variational-bayes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] A conjugate prior is an algebraic convenience, giving a closed-form expression for the posterior; otherwise, numerical integration may be necessary.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Further, conjugate priors may clarify how a likelihood function updates a prior distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] The concept, as well as the term "conjugate prior", were introduced by Howard Raiffa and Robert Schlaifer in their work on Bayesian decision theory.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] A similar concept had been discovered independently by George Alfred Barnard.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] The form of the conjugate prior can generally be determined by inspection of the probability density or probability mass function of a distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] For example, consider a random variable which consists of the number of successes s in n Bernoulli trials with *unknown* probability of success q in [0,1].
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] where $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are chosen to reflect any existing belief or information ( $\alpha =1$ and $\beta =1$ would give a uniform distribution) and $\mathrm {B} (\alpha ,\beta )$ is the Beta function acting as a normalising constant.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] In this context, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are called *hyperparameters* (parameters of the prior), to distinguish them from parameters of the underlying model (here q ).
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] A typical characteristic of conjugate priors is that the dimensionality of the hyperparameters is one greater than that of the parameters of the original distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] If all parameters are scalar values, then there will be one more hyperparameter than parameter; but this also applies to vector-valued and matrix-valued parameters.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] which is another Beta distribution with parameters $(\alpha +s,\beta +f)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This posterior distribution could then be used as the prior for more samples, with the hyperparameters simply adding each extra piece of information as it comes.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] It is often useful to think of the hyperparameters of a conjugate prior distribution corresponding to having observed a certain number of *pseudo-observations* with properties specified by the parameters.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] In general, for nearly all conjugate prior distributions, the hyperparameters can be interpreted in terms of pseudo-observations.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This can help provide intuition behind the often messy update equations and help choose reasonable hyperparameters for a prior.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Starting at different points yields different flows over time.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This is again analogous with the dynamical system defined by a linear operator, but note that since different samples lead to different inferences, this is not simply dependent on time but rather on data over time.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] For related approaches, see Recursive Bayesian estimation and Data assimilation.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Suppose a rental car service operates in your city.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Drivers can drop off and pick up cars anywhere inside the city limits.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] You can find and rent cars using an app.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Suppose you wish to find the probability that you can find a rental car within a short distance of your home address at any time of day.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Suppose we assume the data comes from a Poisson distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This is the Poisson distribution that is *the* most likely to have generated the observed data $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] But the data could also have come from another Poisson distribution, e.g., one with $\lambda =3$ , or $\lambda =2$ , etc.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] In fact, there is an infinite number of Poisson distributions that *could* have generated the observed data.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] With relatively few data points, we should be quite uncertain about which exact Poisson distribution generated this data.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Intuitively we should instead take a weighted average of the probability of $p(x>0|\lambda )$ for each of those Poisson distributions, weighted by how likely they each are, given the data we've observed $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Generally, this quantity is known as the posterior predictive distribution $p(x|\mathbf {x} )=\int _{\theta }p(x|\theta )p(\theta |\mathbf {x} )d\theta \,,$ where x is a new data point, $\mathbf {x}$ is the observed data and $\theta$ are the parameters of the model.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Using Bayes' theorem we can expand $p(\theta |\mathbf {x} )={\frac {p(\mathbf {x} |\theta )p(\theta )}{p(\mathbf {x} )}}\,,$ therefore $p(x|\mathbf {x} )=\int _{\theta }p(x|\theta ){\frac {p(\mathbf {x} |\theta )p(\theta )}{p(\mathbf {x} )}}d\theta \,.$ Generally, this integral is hard to compute.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] However, if you choose a conjugate prior distribution $p(\theta )$ , a closed-form expression can be derived.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This is the posterior predictive column in the tables below.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Returning to our example, if we pick the Gamma distribution as our prior distribution over the rate of the Poisson distributions, then the posterior predictive is the negative binomial distribution, as can be seen from the table below.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] The Gamma distribution is parameterized by two hyperparameters $\alpha ,\beta$ , which we have to choose.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] By looking at plots of the gamma distribution, we pick $\alpha =\beta =2$ , which seems to be a reasonable prior for the average number of cars.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] The choice of prior hyperparameters is inherently subjective and based on prior knowledge.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] This much more conservative estimate reflects the uncertainty in the model parameters, which the posterior predictive takes into account.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] Let *n* denote the number of observations.
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] In all cases below, the data is assumed to consist of *n* points $x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}$ (which will be random vectors in the multivariate cases).
[src:variational-bayes/conjugate-prior] If the likelihood function belongs to the exponential family, then a conjugate prior exists, often also in the exponential family; see Exponential family: Conjugate distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In variational Bayesian methods, the **evidence lower bound** (often abbreviated **ELBO**, also sometimes called the **variational lower bound** or **negative variational free energy**) is a useful lower bound on the log-likelihood of some observed data.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The ELBO is useful because it provides a guarantee on the worst-case for the log-likelihood of some distribution (e.g. $p(X)$ ) which models a set of data.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The actual log-likelihood may be higher (indicating an even better fit to the distribution) because the ELBO includes a Kullback-Leibler divergence (KL divergence) term which decreases the ELBO due to an internal part of the model being inaccurate despite good fit of the model overall.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Thus improving the ELBO score indicates either improving the likelihood of the model $p(X)$ or the fit of a component internal to the model, or both, and the ELBO score makes a good loss function, e.g., for training a deep neural network to improve both the model overall and the internal component.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Let X and Z be random variables, jointly distributed with distribution $p_{\theta }$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] For example, $p_{\theta }(X)$ is the marginal distribution of X , and $p_{\theta }(Z\mid X)$ is the conditional distribution of Z given X .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In the first line, $H[q_{\phi }(z|x)]$ is the entropy of $q_{\phi }$ , which relates the ELBO to the Helmholtz free energy.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In the second line, $\ln p_{\theta }(x)$ is called the *evidence* for x , and $D_{KL}(q_{\phi }(z|x)||p_{\theta }(z|x))$ is the Kullback-Leibler divergence between $q_{\phi }$ and $p_{\theta }$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Suppose we have an observable random variable X , and we want to find its true distribution $p^{*}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This would allow us to generate data by sampling, and estimate probabilities of future events.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] That is, we define a sufficiently large parametric family $\{p_{\theta }\}_{\theta \in \Theta }$ of distributions, then solve for $\min _{\theta }L(p_{\theta },p^{*})$ for some loss function L .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] One possible way to solve this is by considering small variation from $p_{\theta }$ to $p_{\theta +\delta \theta }$ , and solve for $L(p_{\theta },p^{*})-L(p_{\theta +\delta \theta },p^{*})=0$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This is a problem in the calculus of variations, thus it is called the **variational method**.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This defines a family of joint distributions $p_{\theta }$ over $(X,Z)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] It is very easy to sample $(x,z)\sim p_{\theta }$ : simply sample $z\sim p$ , then compute $f_{\theta }(z)$ , and finally sample $x\sim p_{\theta }(\cdot |z)$ using $f_{\theta }(z)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In other words, we have a **generative model** for both the observable and the latent.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Now, we consider a distribution $p_{\theta }$ good, if it is a close approximation of $p^{*}$ : $p_{\theta }(X)\approx p^{*}(X)$ since the distribution on the right side is over X only, the distribution on the left side must marginalize the latent variable Z away.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In general, it's impossible to perform the integral $p_{\theta }(x)=\int p_{\theta }(x|z)p(z)dz$ , forcing us to perform another approximation.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] So define another distribution family $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ and use it to approximate $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This is a **discriminative model** for the latent.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In **Bayesian** language, X is the observed evidence, and Z is the latent/unobserved.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The distribution p over Z is the *prior distribution* over Z , $p_{\theta }(x|z)$ is the likelihood function, and $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ is the *posterior* *distribution* over Z .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Given an observation x , we can *infer* what z likely gave rise to x by computing $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The usual Bayesian method is to estimate the integral $p_{\theta }(x)=\int p_{\theta }(x|z)p(z)dz$ , then compute by Bayes' rule $p_{\theta }(z|x)={\frac {p_{\theta }(x|z)p(z)}{p_{\theta }(x)}}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This is expensive to perform in general, but if we can simply find a good approximation $q_{\phi }(z|x)\approx p_{\theta }(z|x)$ for most $x,z$ , then we can infer z from x cheaply.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Thus, the search for a good $q_{\phi }$ is also called **amortized inference**.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] All in all, we have found a problem of **variational Bayesian inference**.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] This approximation can be seen as overfitting.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In order to maximize $\sum _{i}\ln p_{\theta }(x_{i})$ , it's necessary to find $\ln p_{\theta }(x)$ : $\ln p_{\theta }(x)=\ln \int p_{\theta }(x|z)p(z)dz$ This usually has no closed form and must be estimated.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Unfortunately, this does not give us an unbiased estimator of $\ln p_{\theta }(x)$ , because $\ln$ is nonlinear.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] For fixed x , the optimization $\max _{\theta ,\phi }L(\phi ,\theta ;x)$ simultaneously attempts to maximize $\ln p_{\theta }(x)$ and minimize $D_{\mathit {KL}}(q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)\|p_{\theta }(\cdot |x))$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The ELBO has many possible expressions, each with some different emphasis.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The above form shows that if we sample $z\sim q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ , then $\ln {\frac {p_{\theta }(x,z)}{q_{\phi }(z|x)}}$ is an unbiased estimator of the ELBO.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The above form shows that the ELBO is a lower bound on the evidence $\ln \ p_{\theta }(x)$ , and that maximizing the ELBO with respect to $\phi$ is equivalent to minimizing the KL-divergence from $p_{\theta }(\cdot |x)$ to $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] where again, $\cdot$ ranges over values of z .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] The above form shows that maximizing the ELBO attempts to concentrate $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ on those z that achieve high $\ln \ p_{\theta }(x|z)$ (in other words, high-likelihood explanations of the observed x ) but also to keep $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ close to the prior $p(\cdot )$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] Suppose we take N independent samples from $p^{*}$ , and collect them in the dataset $D=\{x_{1},...,x_{N}\}$ , then we have empirical distribution $q_{D}(x)={\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{i}\delta _{x_{i}}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] In this interpretation, maximizing $L(\phi ,\theta ;D)=\sum _{i}L(\phi ,\theta ;x_{i})$ is minimizing $D_{\mathit {KL}}(q_{D,\phi }(x,z);p_{\theta }(x,z))$ , which upper-bounds the real quantity of interest $D_{\mathit {KL}}(q_{D}(x);p_{\theta }(x))$ via the data-processing inequality.
[src:variational-bayes/evidence-lower-bound] That is, we append a latent space to the observable space, paying the price of a weaker inequality for the sake of more computationally efficient minimization of the KL-divergence.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] A simple interpretation of the KL divergence of P from Q is the expected excess surprisal from using the approximation Q instead of P when the actual is P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] While it is a measure of how different two distributions are and is thus a distance in some sense, it is not actually a metric, which is the most familiar and formal type of distance.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In particular, it is not symmetric in the two distributions (in contrast to variation of information), and does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Instead, in terms of information geometry, it is a type of divergence, a generalization of squared distance, and for certain classes of distributions (notably an exponential family), it satisfies a generalized Pythagorean theorem (which applies to squared distances).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] KL divergence is always a non-negative real number, with value 0 if and only if the two distributions in question are identical.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Consider two probability distributions, a true P and an approximating Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Often, P represents the data, the observations, or a measured probability distribution and distribution Q represents instead a theory, a model, a description, or another approximation of P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] However, sometimes the true distribution P represents a model and the approximating distribution Q represents (simulated) data that are intended to match the true distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The Kullback–Leibler divergence $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ is then interpreted as the average difference of the number of bits required for encoding samples of P using a code optimized for Q rather than one optimized for P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Note that the roles of P and Q can be reversed in some situations where that is easier to compute and the goal is to minimize $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ , such as with the expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) and evidence lower bound (ELBO) computations.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This role-reversal approach exploits that $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)=0$ if and only if $D_{\text{KL}}(Q\parallel P)=0$ and that, in many cases, reducing one has the effect of reducing the other.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] They denoted this by $I(1:2)$ , and defined the "'divergence' between $\mu _{1}$ and $\mu _{2}$ " as the symmetrized quantity $J(1,2)=I(1:2)+I(2:1)$ , which had already been defined and used by Harold Jeffreys in 1948.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In Kullback (1959), the symmetrized form is again referred to as the "divergence", and the relative entropies in each direction are referred to as a "directed divergences" between two distributions; Kullback preferred the term **discrimination information**.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The term "divergence" is in contrast to a distance (metric), since the symmetrized divergence does not satisfy the triangle inequality.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Numerous references to earlier uses of the symmetrized divergence and to other statistical distances are given in Kullback (1959).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The asymmetric "directed divergence" has come to be known as the Kullback–Leibler divergence, while the symmetrized "divergence" is now referred to as the **Jeffreys divergence**.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In other words, it is the expectation of the logarithmic difference between the probabilities P and Q, where the expectation is taken using the probabilities P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Relative entropy is only defined in this way if, for all x, $Q(x)=0$ implies $P(x)=0$ (absolute continuity).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Otherwise, it is often defined as $+\infty$ , but the value $\ +\infty \$ is possible even if $Q(x)\neq 0$ everywhere, provided that ${\mathcal {X}}$ is infinite in extent.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Analogous comments apply to the continuous and general measure cases defined below.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where p and q denote the probability density functions of P and Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where ${\frac {dP(x)}{dQ(x)}}$ is the Radon–Nikodym derivative of P with respect to Q, i.e. the unique Q almost everywhere defined function r on ${\mathcal {X}}$ such that $dP(x)=r(x)dQ(x)$ which exists because P is absolutely continuous with respect to Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Also we assume the expression on the right-hand side exists.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] which is the entropy of P relative to Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The logarithms in these formulae are usually taken to base 2 if information is measured in units of bits, or to base e if information is measured in nats.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Most formulas involving relative entropy hold regardless of the base of the logarithm.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Various conventions exist for referring to $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ in words.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Often it is referred to as the divergence *between* P and Q, but this fails to convey the fundamental asymmetry in the relation.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Sometimes, as in this article, it may be described as the divergence of P *from* Q or as the divergence *from* Q *to* P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This reflects the asymmetry in Bayesian inference, which starts *from* a prior distribution Q and updates *to* the posterior P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Another common way to refer to $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ is as the relative entropy of P *with respect to* Q or the information gain from P over Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Kullback gives the following example (Table 2.1, Example 2.1).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Let P and Q be the distributions shown in the table and figure.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] P is the distribution on the left side of the figure, a binomial distribution with $N=2$ and $p=0.4$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Q is the distribution on the right side of the figure, a discrete uniform distribution with the three possible outcomes *x* = 0, 1, 2 (i.e. ${\mathcal {X}}=\{0,1,2\}$ ), each with probability $p=1/3$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Relative entropies $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ and $D_{\text{KL}}(Q\parallel P)$ are calculated as follows.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In the field of statistics, the Neyman–Pearson lemma states that the most powerful way to distinguish between the two distributions P and Q based on an observation Y (drawn from one of them) is through the log of the ratio of their likelihoods: $\log P(Y)-\log Q(Y)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The KL divergence is the expected value of this statistic if Y is actually drawn from P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Kullback motivated the statistic as an expected log likelihood ratio.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In the context of coding theory, $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ can be constructed by measuring the expected number of extra bits required to code samples from P using a code optimized for Q rather than the code optimized for P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In the context of machine learning, $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ is often called the information gain achieved if P would be used instead of Q which is currently used.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] By analogy with information theory, it is called the *relative entropy* of P with respect to Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Expressed in the language of Bayesian inference, $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ is a measure of the information gained by revising one's beliefs from the prior probability distribution Q to the posterior probability distribution P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In other words, it is the amount of information lost when Q is used to approximate P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In applications, P typically represents the "true" distribution of data, observations, or a precisely calculated theoretical distribution, while Q typically represents a theory, model, description, or approximation of P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In order to find a distribution Q that is closest to P, we can minimize the KL divergence and compute an information projection.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] While it is a statistical distance, it is not a metric, the most familiar type of distance, but instead it is a divergence.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] While metrics are symmetric and generalize *linear* distance, satisfying the triangle inequality, divergences are asymmetric and generalize *squared* distance, in some cases satisfying a generalized Pythagorean theorem.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In general $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ does not equal $D_{\text{KL}}(Q\parallel P)$ , and the asymmetry is an important part of the geometry.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The infinitesimal form of relative entropy, specifically its Hessian, gives a metric tensor that equals the Fisher information metric; see § Fisher information metric.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Fisher information metric on the certain probability distribution let determine the natural gradient for information-geometric optimization algorithms.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Its quantum version is Fubini-study metric.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Relative entropy satisfies a generalized Pythagorean theorem for exponential families (geometrically interpreted as dually flat manifolds), and this allows one to minimize relative entropy by geometric means, for example by information projection and in maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The relative entropy is the Bregman divergence generated by the negative entropy, but it is also of the form of an f-divergence.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] For probabilities over a finite alphabet, it is unique in being a member of both of these classes of statistical divergences.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The application of Bregman divergence can be found in mirror descent.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Consider a growth-optimizing investor in a fair game with mutually exclusive outcomes (e.g. a "horse race" in which the official odds add up to one).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The rate of return expected by such an investor is equal to the relative entropy between the investor's believed probabilities and the official odds.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This is a special case of a much more general connection between financial returns and divergence measures.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Financial risks are connected to $D_{\text{KL}}$ via information geometry.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Investors' views, the prevailing market view, and risky scenarios form triangles on the relevant manifold of probability distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The shape of the triangles determines key financial risks (both qualitatively and quantitatively).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] For instance, obtuse triangles in which investors' views and risk scenarios appear on "opposite sides" relative to the market describe negative risks, acute triangles describe positive exposure, and the right-angled situation in the middle corresponds to zero risk.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Extending this concept, relative entropy can be hypothetically utilised to identify the behaviour of informed investors, if one takes this to be represented by the magnitude and deviations away from the prior expectations of fund flows, for example.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Therefore, relative entropy can be interpreted as the expected extra message-length per datum that must be communicated if a code that is optimal for a given (wrong) distribution Q is used, compared to using a code based on the true distribution P: it is the *excess* entropy.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where $\mathrm {H} (P,Q)$ is the cross entropy of Q relative to P and $\mathrm {H} (P)$ is the entropy of P (which is the same as the cross-entropy of P with itself).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The relative entropy $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ can be thought of geometrically as a statistical distance, a measure of how far the distribution Q is from the distribution P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Geometrically it is a divergence: an asymmetric, generalized form of squared distance.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The cross-entropy $H(P,Q)$ is itself such a measurement (formally a loss function), but it cannot be thought of as a distance, since $H(P,P)=:H(P)$ is not zero.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This can be fixed by subtracting $H(P)$ to make $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ agree more closely with our notion of distance, as the *excess* loss.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The resulting function is asymmetric, and while this can be symmetrized (see § Symmetrised divergence), the asymmetric form is more useful.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] See § Interpretations for more on the geometric interpretation.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Relative entropy relates to "rate function" in the theory of large deviations.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Arthur Hobson proved that relative entropy is the only measure of difference between probability distributions that satisfies some desired properties, which are the canonical extension to those appearing in a commonly used characterization of entropy.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Consequently, mutual information is the only measure of mutual dependence that obeys certain related conditions, since it can be defined in terms of Kullback–Leibler divergence.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Assume that $P>2Q$ with measure strictly greater than 0 .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] It then follows that there must exist some values $\varepsilon >0$ , $\rho >0$ , and $U<\infty$ such that $P\geq 2Q+\varepsilon$ and $Q\leq U$ with measure $\rho$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The previous proof of sufficiency demonstrated that the measure $1-\rho$ component of the series where $P\leq 2Q$ is bounded, so we need only concern ourselves with the behavior of the measure $\rho$ component of the series where $P\geq 2Q+\varepsilon$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The absolute value of the n th term of this component of the series is then lower bounded by ${\frac {1}{n(n-1)}}\rho \left(1+{\frac {\varepsilon }{U}}\right)^{n}$ , which is unbounded as $n\to \infty$ , so the series diverges.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The following result, due to Donsker and Varadhan, is known as **Donsker and Varadhan's variational formula**.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] almost surely with respect to probability measure P, where ${\frac {Q(d\theta )}{P(d\theta )}}$ denotes the Radon-Nikodym derivative of Q with respect to P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where the last inequality follows from $D_{\text{KL}}(Q\parallel Q^{*})\geq 0$ , for which equality occurs if and only if $Q=Q^{*}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The logarithm in the last term must be taken to base e since all terms apart from the last are base-e logarithms of expressions that are either factors of the density function or otherwise arise naturally.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The equation therefore gives a result measured in nats.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Dividing the entire expression above by $\ln(2)$ yields the divergence in bits.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In a numerical implementation, it is helpful to express the result in terms of the Cholesky decompositions $L_{0},L_{1}$ such that $\Sigma _{0}=L_{0}L_{0}^{T}$ and $\Sigma _{1}=L_{1}L_{1}^{T}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Consider two uniform distributions, with the support of $p=[A,B]$ enclosed within $q=[C,D]$ ( $C\leq A<B\leq D$ ).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Intuitively, the information gain to a k times narrower uniform distribution contains $\log _{2}k$ bits.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This connects with the use of bits in computing, where $\log _{2}k$ bits would be needed to identify one element of a k long stream.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where $h(x)$ is reference measure, $T(x)$ is sufficient statistics, $\theta$ is canonical natural parameters, and $A(\theta )$ is the log-partition function.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] For example, for the Poisson distribution with mean $\lambda$ , the sufficient statistics $T(x)=x$ , the natural parameter $\theta =\log \lambda$ , and log partition function $A(\theta )=e^{\theta }$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] As another example, for a normal distribution with unit variance $N(\mu ,1)$ , the sufficient statistics $T(x)=x$ , the natural parameter $\theta =\mu$ , and log partition function $A(\theta )=\mu ^{2}/2$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] While relative entropy is a statistical distance, it is not a metric on the space of probability distributions, but instead it is a divergence.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] While metrics are symmetric and generalize *linear* distance, satisfying the triangle inequality, divergences are asymmetric in general and generalize *squared* distance, in some cases satisfying a generalized Pythagorean theorem.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In general $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ does not equal $D_{\text{KL}}(Q\parallel P)$ , and while this can be symmetrized (see § Symmetrised divergence), the asymmetry is an important part of the geometry.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] It generates a topology on the space of probability distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] where the latter stands for the usual convergence in total variation.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Relative entropy is directly related to the Fisher information metric.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Assume that the probability distributions P and Q are both parameterized by some (possibly multi-dimensional) parameter $\theta$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Consider then two close by values of $P=P(\theta )$ and $Q=P(\theta _{0})$ so that the parameter $\theta$ differs by only a small amount from the parameter value $\theta _{0}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] with $\Delta \theta _{j}=(\theta -\theta _{0})_{j}$ a small change of $\theta$ in the j direction, and $P_{j}\left(\theta _{0}\right)={\frac {\partial P}{\partial \theta _{j}}}(\theta _{0})$ the corresponding rate of change in the probability distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Since relative entropy has an absolute minimum 0 for $P=Q$ , i.e. $\theta =\theta _{0}$ , it changes only to *second* order in the small parameters $\Delta \theta _{j}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Letting $\theta _{0}$ vary (and dropping the subindex 0) the Hessian $g_{jk}(\theta )$ defines a (possibly degenerate) Riemannian metric on the θ parameter space, called the Fisher information metric.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Another information-theoretic metric is variation of information, which is roughly a symmetrization of conditional entropy.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] It is a metric on the set of partitions of a discrete probability space.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] MAUVE is a measure of the statistical gap between two text distributions, such as the difference between text generated by a model and human-written text.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This measure is computed using Kullback–Leibler divergences between the two distributions in a quantized embedding space of a foundation model.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Many of the other quantities of information theory can be interpreted as applications of relative entropy to specific cases.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The self-information, also known as the information content of a signal, random variable, or event is defined as the negative logarithm of the probability of the given outcome occurring.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] is the relative entropy of the probability distribution $P(i)$ from a Kronecker delta representing certainty that $i=m$ — i.e. the number of extra bits that must be transmitted to identify i if only the probability distribution $P(i)$ is available to the receiver, not the fact that $i=m$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] is the number of bits which would have to be transmitted to identify X from N equally likely possibilities, *less* the relative entropy of the uniform distribution on the random variates of X, $P_{U}(X)$ , from the true distribution $P(X)$ — i.e.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] *less* the expected number of bits saved, which would have had to be sent if the value of X were coded according to the uniform distribution $P_{U}(X)$ rather than the true distribution $P(X)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This definition of Shannon entropy forms the basis of E.T.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] is the number of bits which would have to be transmitted to identify X from N equally likely possibilities, *less* the relative entropy of the true joint distribution $P(X,Y)$ from the product distribution $P_{U}(X)P(Y)$ from — i.e.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] *less* the expected number of bits saved which would have had to be sent if the value of X were coded according to the uniform distribution $P_{U}(X)$ rather than the conditional distribution $P(X|Y)$ of X given Y.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] When we have a set of possible events, coming from the distribution p, we can encode them (with a lossless data compression) using entropy encoding.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This compresses the data by replacing each fixed-length input symbol with a corresponding unique, variable-length, prefix-free code (e.g.: the events (A, B, C) with probabilities p = (1/2, 1/4, 1/4) can be encoded as the bits (0, 10, 11)).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] If we know the distribution p in advance, we can devise an encoding that would be optimal (e.g.: using Huffman coding).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Meaning the messages we encode will have the shortest length on average (assuming the encoded events are sampled from p), which will be equal to Shannon's Entropy of p (denoted as $\mathrm {H} (p)$ ).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] However, if we use a different probability distribution (q) when creating the entropy encoding scheme, then a larger number of bits will be used (on average) to identify an event from a set of possibilities.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This new (larger) number is measured by the cross entropy between p and q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The cross entropy between two probability distributions (p and q) measures the average number of bits needed to identify an event from a set of possibilities, if a coding scheme is used based on a given probability distribution q, rather than the "true" distribution p.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] The cross entropy for two distributions p and q over the same probability space is thus defined as follows.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] For explicit derivation of this, see the Motivation section above.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Under this scenario, relative entropies (kl-divergence) can be interpreted as the extra number of bits, on average, that are needed (beyond $\mathrm {H} (p)$ ) for encoding the events because of using q for constructing the encoding scheme instead of p.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In Bayesian statistics, relative entropy can be used as a measure of the information gain in moving from a prior distribution to a posterior distribution: $p(x)\to p(x\mid I)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] which may be less than or greater than the original entropy $\mathrm {H} (p(x\mid I))$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This therefore represents the amount of useful information, or information gain, about X, that has been learned by discovering $Y=y$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] If a further piece of data, $Y_{2}=y_{2}$ , subsequently comes in, the probability distribution for x can be updated further, to give a new best guess $p(x\mid y_{1},y_{2},I)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] All one can say is that on *average*, averaging using $p(y_{2}\mid y_{1},x,I)$ , the two sides will average out.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] A common goal in Bayesian experimental design is to maximise the expected relative entropy between the prior and the posterior.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] When posteriors are approximated to be Gaussian distributions, a design maximising the expected relative entropy is called Bayes d-optimal.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Another name for this quantity, given to it by I.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Good, is the expected weight of evidence for $H_{1}$ over $H_{0}$ to be expected from each sample.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Either of the two quantities can be used as a utility function in Bayesian experimental design, to choose an optimal next question to investigate: but they will in general lead to rather different experimental strategies.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] On the entropy scale of *information gain* there is very little difference between near certainty and absolute certainty—coding according to a near certainty requires hardly any more bits than coding according to an absolute certainty.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] These two different scales of loss function for uncertainty are *both* useful, according to how well each reflects the particular circumstances of the problem in question.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] MDI can be seen as an extension of Laplace's Principle of Insufficient Reason, and the Principle of Maximum Entropy of E.T.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In particular, it is the natural extension of the principle of maximum entropy from discrete to continuous distributions, for which Shannon entropy ceases to be so useful (see *differential entropy*), but the relative entropy continues to be just as relevant.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] In the engineering literature, MDI is sometimes called the **Principle of Minimum Cross-Entropy** (MCE) or **Minxent** for short.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] which is appropriate if one is trying to choose an adequate approximation to p.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] However, this is just as often *not* the task one is trying to achieve.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] Instead, just as often it is m that is some fixed prior reference measure, and p that one is attempting to optimise by minimising $D_{\text{KL}}(p\parallel m)$ subject to some constraint.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p01] This has led to some ambiguity in the literature, with some authors attempting to resolve the inconsistency by redefining cross-entropy to be $D_{\text{KL}}(p\parallel m)$ , rather than $\mathrm {H} (p,m)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Surprisals add where probabilities multiply.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] The surprisal for an event of probability p is defined as $s=-k\ln p$ .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] If k is $\left\{1,1/\ln 2,1.38\times 10^{-23}\right\}$ then surprisal is in $\{$ nats, bits, or $J/K\}$ so that, for instance, there are N bits of surprisal for landing all "heads" on a toss of N coins.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Best-guess states (e.g. for atoms in a gas) are inferred by maximizing the *average surprisal* S (entropy) for a given set of control parameters (like pressure P or volume V).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] This constrained entropy maximization, both classically and quantum mechanically, minimizes Gibbs availability in entropy units $A\equiv -k\ln Z$ where Z is a constrained multiplicity or partition function.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] When temperature T is fixed, free energy ( $T\times A$ ) is also minimized.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Thus if $T,V$ and number of molecules N are constant, the Helmholtz free energy $F\equiv U-TS$ (where U is energy and S is entropy) is minimized as a system "equilibrates." If T and P are held constant (say during processes in your body), the Gibbs free energy $G=U+PV-TS$ is minimized instead.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] The change in free energy under these conditions is a measure of available work that might be done in the process.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Thus available work for an ideal gas at constant temperature $T_{o}$ and pressure $P_{o}$ is $W=\Delta G=NkT_{o}\Theta (V/V_{o})$ where $V_{o}=NkT_{o}/P_{o}$ and $\Theta (x)=x-1-\ln x\geq 0$ (see also Gibbs inequality).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] More generally the work available relative to some ambient is obtained by multiplying ambient temperature $T_{o}$ by relative entropy or *net surprisal* $\Delta I\geq 0,$ defined as the average value of $k\ln(p/p_{o})$ where $p_{o}$ is the probability of a given state under ambient conditions.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] The resulting contours of constant relative entropy, shown at right for a mole of Argon at standard temperature and pressure, for example put limits on the conversion of hot to cold as in flame-powered air-conditioning or in the unpowered device to convert boiling-water to ice-water discussed here.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Thus relative entropy measures thermodynamic availability in bits.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] In quantum information science the minimum of $D_{\text{KL}}(P\parallel Q)$ over all separable states Q can also be used as a measure of entanglement in the state P.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Just as relative entropy of "actual from ambient" measures thermodynamic availability, relative entropy of "reality from a model" is also useful even if the only clues we have about reality are some experimental measurements.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] In the former case relative entropy describes *distance to equilibrium* or (when multiplied by ambient temperature) the amount of *available work*, while in the latter case it tells you about surprises that reality has up its sleeve or, in other words, *how much the model has yet to learn*.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Although this tool for evaluating models against systems that are accessible experimentally may be applied in any field, its application to selecting a statistical model via Akaike information criterion are particularly well described in papers and a book by Burnham and Anderson.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] In a nutshell the relative entropy of reality from a model may be estimated, to within a constant additive term, by a function of the deviations observed between data and the model's predictions (like the mean squared deviation) .
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Estimates of such divergence for models that share the same additive term can in turn be used to select among models.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] When trying to fit parametrized models to data there are various estimators which attempt to minimize relative entropy, such as maximum likelihood and maximum spacing estimators.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] which they referred to as the "divergence", though today the "KL divergence" refers to the asymmetric function (see § Etymology for the evolution of the term).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] This function is symmetric and nonnegative, and had already been defined and used by Harold Jeffreys in 1948; it is accordingly called the **Jeffreys divergence**.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] This quantity has sometimes been used for feature selection in classification problems, where P and Q are the conditional Probability density functions of a feature under two different classes.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] In the Banking and Finance industries, this quantity is referred to as **Population Stability Index** (**PSI**), and is used to assess distributional shifts in model features through time.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] which can be interpreted as the expected information gain about X from discovering which probability distribution X is drawn from, P or Q, if they currently have probabilities $\lambda$ and $1-\lambda$ respectively.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] We can also interpret $D_{\text{JS}}$ as the capacity of a noisy information channel with two inputs giving the output distributions P and Q.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] The Jensen–Shannon divergence, like all f-divergences, is *locally* proportional to the Fisher information metric.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] It is similar to the Hellinger metric (in the sense that it induces the same affine connection on a statistical manifold).
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Furthermore, the Jensen–Shannon divergence can be generalized using abstract statistical M-mixtures relying on an abstract mean M.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] There are many other important measures of probability distance.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Some of these are particularly connected with relative entropy.
[src:variational-bayes/kullback-leibler-divergence-p02] Other notable measures of distance include the Hellinger distance, *histogram intersection*, *Chi-squared statistic*, *quadratic form distance*, *match distance*, *Kolmogorov–Smirnov distance*, and *earth mover's distance*.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Such models consider many individual components that interact with each other.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The main idea of MFT is to replace all interactions to any one body with an average or effective interaction, sometimes called a *molecular field*.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] This reduces any many-body problem into an effective one-body problem.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The ease of solving MFT problems means that some insight into the behavior of the system can be obtained at a lower computational cost.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] MFT has since been applied to a wide range of fields outside of physics, including statistical inference, graphical models, neuroscience, artificial intelligence, epidemic models, queueing theory, computer-network performance and game theory, as in the quantal response equilibrium.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The idea first appeared in physics (statistical mechanics) in the work of Pierre Curie and Pierre Weiss to describe phase transitions.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] MFT has been used in the Bragg–Williams approximation, models on Bethe lattice, Landau theory, Curie-Weiss law for magnetic susceptibility, Flory–Huggins solution theory, and Scheutjens–Fleer theory.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Systems with many (sometimes infinite) degrees of freedom are generally hard to solve exactly or compute in closed, analytic form, except for some simple cases (e.g. certain Gaussian random-field theories, the 1D Ising model).
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Often combinatorial problems arise that make things like computing the partition function of a system difficult.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] MFT is an approximation method that often makes the original problem to be solvable and open to calculation, and in some cases MFT may give very accurate approximations.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In field theory, the Hamiltonian may be expanded in terms of the magnitude of fluctuations around the mean of the field.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In this context, MFT can be viewed as the "zeroth-order" expansion of the Hamiltonian in fluctuations.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Physically, this means that an MFT system has no fluctuations, but this coincides with the idea that one is replacing all interactions with a "mean-field”.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Quite often, MFT provides a convenient launch point for studying higher-order fluctuations.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] For example, when computing the partition function, studying the combinatorics of the interaction terms in the Hamiltonian can sometimes at best produce perturbation results or Feynman diagrams that correct the mean-field approximation.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In general, dimensionality plays an active role in determining whether a mean-field approach will work for any particular problem.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] There is sometimes a critical dimension above which MFT is valid and below which it is not.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Heuristically, many interactions are replaced in MFT by one effective interaction.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] So if the field or particle exhibits many random interactions in the original system, they tend to cancel each other out, so the mean effective interaction and MFT will be more accurate.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] This is true in cases of high dimensionality, when the Hamiltonian includes long-range forces, or when the particles are extended (e.g. polymers).
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The Ginzburg criterion is the formal expression of how fluctuations render MFT a poor approximation, often depending upon the number of spatial dimensions in the system of interest.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The formal basis for mean-field theory is the Bogoliubov inequality.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where $S_{0}$ is the entropy, and F and $F_{0}$ are Helmholtz free energies.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The average is taken over the equilibrium ensemble of the reference system with Hamiltonian ${\mathcal {H}}_{0}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where $\xi _{i}$ are the degrees of freedom of the individual components of our statistical system (atoms, spins and so forth), one can consider sharpening the upper bound by minimising the right side of the inequality.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The minimising reference system is then the "best" approximation to the true system using non-correlated degrees of freedom and is known as the **mean field approximation**.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where ${\mathcal {P}}$ is the set of pairs that interact, the minimising procedure can be carried out formally.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Define $\operatorname {Tr} _{i}f(\xi _{i})$ as the generalized sum of the observable f over the degrees of freedom of the single component (sum for discrete variables, integrals for continuous ones).
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where $Z_{0}$ is the partition function.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In order to minimise, we take the derivative with respect to the single-degree-of-freedom probabilities $P_{0}^{(i)}$ using a Lagrange multiplier to ensure proper normalization.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Mean field theory can be applied to a number of physical systems so as to study phenomena such as phase transitions.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The Bogoliubov inequality, shown above, can be used to find the dynamics of a mean field model of the two-dimensional Ising lattice.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] A magnetisation function can be calculated from the resultant approximate free energy.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The first step is choosing a more tractable approximation of the true Hamiltonian.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] By the Bogoliubov inequality, simplifying this quantity and calculating the magnetisation function that minimises the variational free energy yields the best approximation to the actual magnetisation.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Equating the effective field felt by all spins to a mean spin value relates the variational approach to the suppression of fluctuations.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The physical interpretation of the magnetisation function is then a field of mean values for individual spins.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Consider the Ising model on a d -dimensional lattice.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where the $\sum _{\langle i,j\rangle }$ indicates summation over the pair of nearest neighbors $\langle i,j\rangle$ , and $s_{i},s_{j}=\pm 1$ are neighboring Ising spins.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Let us transform our spin variable by introducing the fluctuation from its mean value $m_{i}\equiv \langle s_{i}\rangle$ .
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] where we define $\delta s_{i}\equiv s_{i}-m_{i}$ ; this is the *fluctuation* of the spin.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] If we expand the right side, we obtain one term that is entirely dependent on the mean values of the spins and independent of the spin configurations.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] This is the trivial term, which does not affect the statistical properties of the system.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The next term is the one involving the product of the mean value of the spin and the fluctuation value.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Finally, the last term involves a product of two fluctuation values.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] These fluctuations are enhanced at low dimensions, making MFT a better approximation for high dimensions.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In addition, we expect that the mean value of each spin is site-independent, since the Ising chain is translationally invariant.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] The summation over neighboring spins can be rewritten as $\sum _{\langle i,j\rangle }={\frac {1}{2}}\sum _{i}\sum _{j\in nn(i)}$ , where $nn(i)$ means "nearest neighbor of i ", and the $1/2$ prefactor avoids double counting, since each bond participates in two spins.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] At this point, the Ising Hamiltonian has been *decoupled* into a sum of one-body Hamiltonians with an *effective mean field* $h^{\text{eff.}}=h+Jzm$ , which is the sum of the external field h and of the *mean field* induced by the neighboring spins.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] It is worth noting that this mean field directly depends on the number of nearest neighbors and thus on the dimension of the system (for instance, for a hypercubic lattice of dimension d , $z=2d$ ).
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] This is a closed and exact expression for the partition function of the system.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] We may obtain the free energy of the system and calculate critical exponents.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In particular, we can obtain the magnetization m as a function of $h^{\text{eff.}}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] We thus have two equations between m and $h^{\text{eff.}}$ , allowing us to determine m as a function of temperature.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] This shows that MFT can account for the ferromagnetic phase transition.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] Variationally minimisation like mean field theory can be also be used in statistical inference.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] In mean field theory, the mean field appearing in the single-site problem is a time-independent scalar or vector quantity.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] However, this isn't always the case: in a variant of mean field theory called dynamical mean field theory (DMFT), the mean field becomes a time-dependent quantity.
[src:variational-bayes/mean-field-theory] For instance, DMFT can be applied to the Hubbard model to study the metal–Mott-insulator transition.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] To derive a lower bound for the marginal likelihood (sometimes called the *evidence*) of the observed data (i.e. the marginal probability of the data given the model, with marginalization performed over unobserved variables).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is typically used for performing model selection, the general idea being that a higher marginal likelihood for a given model indicates a better fit of the data by that model and hence a greater probability that the model in question was the one that generated the data.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, whereas Monte Carlo techniques provide a numerical approximation to the exact posterior using a set of samples, variational Bayes provides a locally-optimal, exact analytical solution to an approximation of the posterior.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As in EM, it finds a set of optimal parameter values, and it has the same alternating structure as does EM, based on a set of interlocked (mutually dependent) equations that cannot be solved analytically.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For many applications, variational Bayes produces solutions of comparable accuracy to Gibbs sampling at greater speed.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, deriving the set of equations used to update the parameters iteratively often requires a large amount of work compared with deriving the comparable Gibbs sampling equations.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is the case even for many models that are conceptually quite simple, as is demonstrated below in the case of a basic non-hierarchical model with only two parameters and no latent variables.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The similarity (or dissimilarity) is measured in terms of a dissimilarity function $d(Q;P)$ and hence inference is performed by selecting the distribution $Q(\mathbf {Z} )$ that minimizes $d(Q;P)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The most common type of variational Bayes uses the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-divergence) of *Q* from *P* as the choice of dissimilarity function.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This choice makes this minimization tractable.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that *Q* and *P* are reversed from what one might expect.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This use of reversed KL-divergence is conceptually similar to the expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The marginalization over $\mathbf {Z}$ to calculate $P(\mathbf {X} )$ in the denominator is typically intractable, because, for example, the search space of $\mathbf {Z}$ is combinatorially large.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Therefore, we seek an approximation, using $Q(\mathbf {Z} )\approx P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As the *log-evidence* $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ is fixed with respect to Q , maximizing the final term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ minimizes the KL divergence of Q from P .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By appropriate choice of Q , ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ becomes tractable to compute and to maximize.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence we have both an analytical approximation Q for the posterior $P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ , and a lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ for the log-evidence $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ (since the KL-divergence is non-negative).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is known as the (negative) **variational free energy** in analogy with thermodynamic free energy because it can also be expressed as a negative energy $\operatorname {E} _{Q}[\log P(\mathbf {Z} ,\mathbf {X} )]$ plus the entropy of Q .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is also known as **Evidence Lower Bound**, abbreviated as **ELBO**, to emphasize that it is a lower (worst-case) bound on the log-evidence of the data.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term $\zeta (\mathbf {X} )$ is often called the evidence lower bound (**ELBO**) in practice, since $P(\mathbf {X} )\geq \zeta (\mathbf {X} )=\exp({\mathcal {L}}(Q^{*}))$ , as shown above.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By interchanging the roles of $\mathbf {Z} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {Z} _{2},$ we can iteratively compute the approximated $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{1})$ and $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{2})$ of the true model's marginals $P(\mathbf {Z} _{1}\mid \mathbf {X} )$ and $P(\mathbf {Z} _{2}\mid \mathbf {X} ),$ respectively.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Although this iterative scheme is guaranteed to converge monotonically, the converged $Q^{*}$ is only a local minimizer of $D_{\mathrm {KL} }(Q\parallel P)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The constant in the above expression is related to the normalizing constant (the denominator in the expression above for $q_{j}^{*}$ ) and is usually reinstated by inspection, as the rest of the expression can usually be recognized as being a known type of distribution (e.g.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This creates circular dependencies between the parameters of the distributions over variables in one partition and the expectations of variables in the other partitions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An algorithm of this sort is guaranteed to converge.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula for the distribution's parameters will be expressed in terms of the prior distributions' hyperparameters (which are known constants), but also in terms of expectations of functions of variables in other partitions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually these expectations can be simplified into functions of expectations of the variables themselves (i.e. the means); sometimes expectations of squared variables (which can be related to the variance of the variables), or expectations of higher powers (i.e. higher moments) also appear.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In most cases, the other variables' distributions will be from known families, and the formulas for the relevant expectations can be looked up.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, those formulas depend on those distributions' parameters, which depend in turn on the expectations about other variables.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result is that the formulas for the parameters of each variable's distributions can be expressed as a series of equations with mutual, nonlinear dependencies among the variables.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually, it is not possible to solve this system of equations directly.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, as described above, the dependencies suggest a simple iterative algorithm, which in most cases is guaranteed to converge.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An example will make this process clearer.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The following theorem is referred to as a duality formula for variational inference.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It explains some important properties of the variational distributions used in variational Bayes methods.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Theorem Consider two probability spaces $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ and $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},Q)$ with $Q\ll P$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that there is a common dominating probability measure $\lambda$ such that $P\ll \lambda$ and $Q\ll \lambda$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Let h denote any real-valued random variable on $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ that satisfies $\exp h\in L_{1}(P)$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] almost surely with respect to probability measure Q , where $p(\theta )=dP/d\lambda$ and $q(\theta )=dQ/d\lambda$ denote the Radon–Nikodym derivatives of the probability measures P and Q with respect to $\lambda$ , respectively.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Consider a simple non-hierarchical Bayesian model consisting of a set of i.i.d. observations from a Gaussian distribution, with unknown mean and variance.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the following, we work through this model in great detail to illustrate the workings of the variational Bayes method.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For mathematical convenience, in the following example we work in terms of the precision — i.e. the reciprocal of the variance (or in a multivariate Gaussian, the inverse of the covariance matrix) — rather than the variance itself.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We place conjugate prior distributions on the unknown mean $\mu$ and precision $\tau$ , i.e. the mean also follows a Gaussian distribution while the precision follows a gamma distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The hyperparameters $\mu _{0},\lambda _{0},a_{0}$ and $b_{0}$ in the prior distributions are fixed, given values.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] They can be set to small positive numbers to give broad prior distributions indicating ignorance about the prior distributions of $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that $q(\mu ,\tau )=q(\mu )q(\tau )$ , i.e. that the posterior distribution factorizes into independent factors for $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This type of assumption underlies the variational Bayesian method.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The true posterior distribution does not in fact factor this way (in fact, in this simple case, it is known to be a Gaussian-gamma distribution), and hence the result we obtain will be an approximation.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the above derivation, C , $C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ refer to values that are constant with respect to $\mu$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that the term $\operatorname {E} _{\tau }[\ln p(\tau )]$ is not a function of $\mu$ and will have the same value regardless of the value of $\mu$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence in line 3 we can absorb it into the constant term at the end.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The last line is simply a quadratic polynomial in $\mu$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Since this is the logarithm of $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ , we can see that $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ itself is a Gaussian distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that all of the above steps can be shortened by using the formula for the sum of two quadratics.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The derivation of $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is similar to above, although we omit some of the details for the sake of brevity.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Exponentiating both sides, we can see that $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is a gamma distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In each case, the parameters for the distribution over one of the variables depend on expectations taken with respect to the other variable.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that there are circular dependencies among the formulas for $\lambda _{N}$ and $b_{N}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Initialize $\lambda _{N}$ to some arbitrary value.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $\lambda _{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $b_{N}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $b_{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $\lambda _{N}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Repeat the last two steps until convergence (i.e. until neither value has changed more than some small amount).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It can be shown that this algorithm is guaranteed to converge to a local maximum.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note also that the posterior distributions have the same form as the corresponding prior distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We did *not* assume this; the only assumption we made was that the distributions factorize, and the form of the distributions followed naturally.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It turns out (see below) that the fact that the posterior distributions have the same form as the prior distributions is not a coincidence, but a general result whenever the prior distributions are members of the exponential family, which is the case for most of the standard distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Partition the unobserved variables into two or more subsets, over which the independent factors will be derived.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] There is no universal procedure for doing this; creating too many subsets yields a poor approximation, while creating too few makes the entire variational Bayes procedure intractable.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Typically, the first split is to separate the parameters and latent variables; often, this is enough by itself to produce a tractable result.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that the partitions are called $\mathbf {Z} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {Z} _{M}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Fill in the formula for the joint probability distribution using the graphical model.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Any component conditional distributions that don't involve any of the variables in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ can be ignored; they will be folded into the constant term.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Simplify the formula and apply the expectation operator, following the above example.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Ideally, this should simplify into expectations of basic functions of variables not in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ (e.g. first or second raw moments, expectation of a logarithm, etc.).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the variational Bayes procedure to work well, these expectations should generally be expressible analytically as functions of the parameters and/or hyperparameters of the distributions of these variables.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In all cases, these expectation terms are constants with respect to the variables in the current partition.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The functional form of the formula with respect to the variables in the current partition indicates the type of distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, exponentiating the formula generates the probability density function (PDF) of the distribution (or at least, something proportional to it, with unknown normalization constant).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the overall method to be tractable, it should be possible to recognize the functional form as belonging to a known distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Significant mathematical manipulation may be required to convert the formula into a form that matches the PDF of a known distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this can be done, the normalization constant can be reinstated by definition, and equations for the parameters of the known distribution can be derived by extracting the appropriate parts of the formula.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this procedure can be applied to all partitions, the result is a set of mutually linked equations specifying the optimum values of all parameters.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An expectation–maximization (EM) type procedure is then applied, picking an initial value for each parameter and the iterating through a series of steps, where at each step we cycle through the equations, updating each parameter in turn.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Due to all of the mathematical manipulations involved, it is easy to lose track of the big picture.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] "Analytical approximation" means that a formula can be written down for the posterior distribution.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula generally consists of a product of well-known probability distributions, each of which *factorizes* over a set of unobserved variables (i.e. it is conditionally independent of the other variables, given the observed data).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This formula is not the true posterior distribution, but an approximation to it; in particular, it will generally agree fairly closely in the lowest moments of the unobserved variables, e.g. the mean and variance.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result of all of the mathematical manipulations is (1) the identity of the probability distributions making up the factors, and (2) mutually dependent formulas for the parameters of these distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual values of these parameters are computed numerically, through an alternating iterative procedure much like EM.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Variational Bayes (VB) is often compared with expectation–maximization (EM).
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual numerical procedure is quite similar, in that both are alternating iterative procedures that successively converge on optimum parameter values.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The initial steps to derive the respective procedures are also vaguely similar, both starting out with formulas for probability densities and both involving significant amounts of mathematical manipulations.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, there are a number of differences.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Most important is *what* is being computed.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] In other words, $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} )$ is a product of single-observation multinomial distributions, and factors over each individual $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ , which is distributed as a single-observation multinomial distribution with parameters $r_{nk}$ for $k=1\dots K$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] which is a standard result for categorical distributions.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] These can be converted from proportional to absolute values by normalizing over k so that the corresponding values sum to 1.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] The update equations for the parameters $\alpha _{1\dots K}$ of the variable $\mathbf {\pi }$ depend on the statistic $N_{k}$ , which depends in turn on $r_{nk}$ .
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] An M-step that uses the new value of $r_{nk}$ to compute new values of all the other parameters.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] Note that these steps correspond closely with the standard EM algorithm to derive a maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) solution for the parameters of a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:variational-bayes/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] This is a general result that holds true for all prior distributions derived from the exponential family.
